The GMCS IT department was recognized at today’s school Board meeting. This team is vital in delivering Remote Learning Services, preparing 11,000 student computer devices and 9,600 internet hotspots for students. These individuals are also the team providing support to students and educators as we navigate our current educational landscape.

This team had a monumental task in getting our technology ready. Huge thank you to this great team for your continued support throughout our district. We are GMCS!

Due revised communications from the New Mexico Public Education Department (NM PED) and ongoing Union Negotiations, Gallup-McKinley County Schools is canceling school for students for three days on 8/17/20-8/19/20. Parents/Guardians can still pick up their student’s computing devices, other school materials and school meals on these three days.

Student’s first day of school will begin on Thursday, 8/20/20.

Thank you for your patience and understanding during these difficult times. If you have questions or need additional information, please contact your student(s) school site.

post_text:
Tohatchi High School Student Kick-Off:

We are so incredibly excited to welcome our students back! To kick the year off, students will need to stop by the campus on Monday, August 17 to pick up supplies. Included will be: a district-owned personal laptop, a student supply kit, a class schedule, and the THS official virtual learning schedule. Please note that families will need to sign an appropriate use form as well as a form outlining responsibilities for the technology. Because of this students will need a legal parent/legal guardian to accompany them when they pick up and we will only be able to release equipment to each student and parent (no one will be able to pick up for a friend). Parent/Guardian and student only, please do not bring more than 1 person with you to pick up items.
Distribution will be done in the gym and in time slots organized by last name. Please come at your designated time:

• Monday 8/17/20
o A-L: 9:00am-12:00pm
o M-Z: 1:00pm-4:00pm

We look forward to seeing everyone at their time Monday and can't wait to get the year started!
Kristi Del Curto

Parents, it is very important that we can reach you to provide you information on reopening activities. Please follow these steps to update your information.

Annual Update of Information Forms:

If you have a student returning for the 2020-2021 school year, then please see instructions below
Fill out Annual Update of Information packet (PDF Packet)

You can pick up a packet at the school site
Email StudentInfo@gmcs.org to have the packet mailed to you
Make sure you sign and date all pages
If your physical address has changed, make sure you include Physical address verification (utility bill or equivalent)
Methods to return completed packet:
a) Scan and email to StudentInfo@gmcs.org
b) Deliver to the school site the student is enrolled with
c) Mail to the following address and it will be forwarded to the intended school site:
GMCS/Student Information
PO Box 1318
Gallup, NM 87305
If you have any questions or concerns, please email them to StudentInfo@gmcs.org or call Lori Clark at 505-721-2202

GMCS Transportation Staff have been busy getting ready for the New School Year. We’ve got over 65 brand new buses distributed across the District and every bus in the District has been upgraded to provide WiFi services to those students who are returning under Option #1: Hybrid (at least 2 days a week in-person) option. The District will also be using buses to assist with meal distribution for students who chose Option #2: Remote/Online. New sanitizing procedures, safety measures and social distancing protocols will be presented during Monday’s Board meeting.

post_text: An obvious attempt by the American Federation of Teachers union (AFT), which oversees McFuse, to deflect from their failed attempts at holding negotiations in GMCS hostage by postponing the school calendar and staff raises. This effort also potentially delayed many employees paychecks which would have been catastrophic. The facts are that AFT asked for a hearing, tried for 3 hours to prove a weak argument, and then asked to settle for what GMCS had already offered. This is a drastically different story than the one eluded to in this narrative. Despite efforts to delay our students’ education, GMCS will continue to advocate for our students and employees for a safe and productive start to the school year. Listen to Monday’s GMCS Board Meeting for information about the school calendar, safety measures, parents options for online or in-person learning for their students, staff raises, and other important information.

post_text:
We know that some families are hesitant about schools opening again, but we want you to know we are working hard to provide a sanitary learning environment, structured social distancing and increased technology for remote learning when students are not in school. Each student will have access to a device in school or at home during remote learning.

Parents will have the opportunity soon to complete a form to let us know if their students will be returning to the hybrid (2 days a week) on-site learning model or if their students will be participating in remote learning only. These forms will be mailed to parents next week and will be available for download on gmcs.org.

If you have questions, concerns or feedback, please email us at parent.reopening@gmcs.org
#GMCS #iamgmcs #wecare #reentryforschool

post_text:
Exciting News from Hiroshi Miyamura High School!

We are excited to announce that Hiroshi Miyamura High School has “ZERO” Covid-19 patients in the facility and the number of patients has fortunately been significantly below capacity during this entire pandemic. We appreciate the communities efforts in significantly reducing the Covid-19 threat. Hiroshi Miyamura High School will be professionally cleaned, blessed, and ready for students to return in the fall. Given that the facility has zero patients we hope the State of New Mexico considers releasing the building sooner than August so that our “Miyamura Patriots” can soon look forward to athletics and some normalcy sooner than later in their own school building and gymnasium. Our students have sacrificed for the greater good of the community and now it’s time to help them get their high school memories back since the facility is not utilized at all at this time for patients. Our students and staff deserve to have their school back! Stay tuned for further developments.

Pre-k and Preschool Enrollment Information.

Families need to call the school office and have their child put on a list. Rocky View area children can contact Indian Hills or Jefferson.
Alternative Preschool/PreK enrollment process: Approved 5-27-20
If we are not able to complete the ASQ screenings during May due to covid 19 restrictions.

Alternative enrollment plan for preschool age children:
• Priorities all 4 year old students and take them in the order they are on the waiting list.
• Keep a list of 3 year old children interested in attending preschool
• Complete the Ages and Stages Questioner (ASQ) when school resumes in the Fall.
Shannon McFarland
Coordinator of Early Childhood Services
Phone:505 721-1013
Email:smcfarla@gmcs.org

Families currently on SNAP benefits will see additional funds on their current EBT account by the end of the month.

Families students that were receiving free and reduced lunch or attend a Community Eligibility School (CEP) or Provision 2 school where all students eat free, will receive a P-EBT benefit card in the mail. These should be out by early June.

Families who have had a change in economic circumstance due to the COVID-19 crisis can fill out a new household application via their local school district food service office.

Districts and school sites still need to serve meals until the end of their school year. All students and children can currently still pick up breakfast and lunch meals offered.

Governor Michelle Lujan Grisham
March 23 at 3:50 PM ·

Today I am announcing that effective tomorrow at 8 AM, New Mexico will be under a statewide stay-at-home instruction. All New Mexicans are instructed to stay at home except for outings essential to health, safety, and welfare.

It is urgently important that New Mexicans understand: You must stay home. Don’t panic – but it's no time for business as usual. This is life-and-death, and the most important thing the average New Mexican can do to help, right now, is stay at home. All businesses except those deemed essential to public health, safety and well-being will be ordered closed. Our society must continue to operate – but in an extremely limited way. This is the only way to slow the spread of COVID-19. More information here: https://bit.ly/2QHgSwD

Essential services include health care services, grocery stores, pharmacies, gas stations, utilities, child care for essential workers, banks & credit unions, shelters, emergency services, & infrastructure operations. See the full list of essential services and find more information here: https://bit.ly/39cCwPN

TOHATCHI GIRLS BASKETBALL RECAP:

The No. 3 seed Tohatchi Lady Cougars lost were beaten in the N.M. Class 3A girls basketball state championship game, falling to No. 1 seed Navajo Prep 43-33 Friday at Dreamstyle Arena.
Krystal Benally scored all 12 points for the Cougars in the first half, with the Eagles taking a 23-12 halftime lead.
Tohatchi got within 24-20 in the third quarter, but Navajo Prep pulled back ahead for a 34-23 lead going into the final eight minutes.
Tohatchi had got within 10 points twice in the fourth quarter, once at 37-27 on a goal by Benally and again at 43-33 on a goal by Montana Soto.
But the aggressive defense by Navajo Prep never let Tohatchi get closer.
Tohatchi ended the year with a 23-7 record, with three of those losses coming to Navajo Prep.
Navajo Prep finished with a 28-2 record.

post_text:
Tohatchi Cougar Update:
The No. 3 seed Tohatchi Cougars advanced to the N.M. Class 3A girls basketball championship game with a 63-48 victory over the No. 2 seed Tularosa Wildcats in the semifinals at Santa Ana Star Center Thursday night.
The Lady Cougars (23-7) will face No. 1 seed Navajo Prep Friday at 3 p.m. in the championship game at Dreamstyle Arena.
Montana Soto and Cameron Tsosie each scored 15 points to lead the Cougars. Brooke Badonie scored 14 points and Krystal Benally scored 10 points to contribute to the victory.
Tohatchi jumped out to a big lead in the first half, taking a 36-11 lead at halftime.
The game was played without spectators.

GHS UPDATE:
The No.2 seed Gallup Bengals fell to the No. 3 seed Highland Hornets 69-49 in the semifinals of the N.M. Class 4A state boys basketball tournament at Dreamstyle Arena Thursday night.
The Bengals led 14-13 at the end of the first quarter. Highland rallied and took a 30-27 lead at halftime.
Highland used a 25-5 advantage in the third quarter to take a 55-32 lead over the Bengals.
The Bengals end the year with a 25-6 record.
Highland (21-10) will play No. 1 Valley in the Class 4A championship Saturday at 4 p.m. at Dreamstyle Arena.

GHS GAME RECAP-Good luck!

The No. 2 seed Gallup Bengals advanced to the semifinals of the N.M. state boys basketball tournament with a 72-47 quarterfinal win over the No. 7 seed Espanola Sundevils Wednesday at Dreamstyle Arena.
Joaquin Ortega scored 19 points and Quinn Atazhoon scored 18 points to lead the Bengals.
Gallup ended the first quarter with a 9-0 run to take a 13-7 lead.
Gallup never trailed from there. Gallup led 31-23 at halftime and led 48-32 at the end of the third quarter.
The Bengals, now 25-5, will face No. 3 seed Highland at 6:30 p.m. Thursday in the Class 4A semifinals at Dreamstyle Arena.

post_text:
The No. 10 seed Gallup Bengals were eliminated from the 2020 N.M. girls state basketball tournament, losing 61-54 to the No. 2 seed Kirtland Central Broncos in the quarterfinal round at Dreamstyle Arena (The Pit) Tuesday night.
KC took the early, jumping on top 20-10 after the first quarter. The Broncos led 32-23 at halftime.
Gallup got within one point to open the third quarter, but the Broncos fought back to take a 42-39 lead by the end of the period.
Gallup was led by Jordan Joe with 19 points and Jordan Hanley with 17 points.
Gallup head coach Todd Mc Broom said he was proud of his team.
"For three years, we've won 20-something games (each year)," McBroom said. "That's because of them (the players)."
Gallup ended the year with a 22-10 record.
Gallup's Justine Tso said, "We were able to grow as a team (this season). It taught us many life lessons."
Tatelyn Manheimer led KC with 16 points.

With a full house of Cougar fans that included Navajo Nation President Jonathan Nez, the No. 3 seed Tohatchi Lady Cougars defeated the No. 14 seed Dexter Demons 52-32 in the first round of the New Mexico Class 3A girls state basketball tournament Friday night at Tohatchi High School.
Tohatchi was led by Cameron Tsosie with 17 points, Montana Soto with 14 points and Krystal Benally with 12 points.
The Cougars, who led the entire game, had a 27-8 halftime lead.
The Cougars advanced to the quarterfinals of the state tournament. The Cougars will play No. 6 seed Santa Fe Indian on Tuesday, March 10 at 8:15 p.m. at Santa Ana Star Center.
Santa Fe Indian beat No.11 Thoreau 51-45 on Friday.

post_text:
Miyamura High School held an informational meeting Monday at Miyamura High School to discuss the new 9th grade Gateways program.
Miyamura High School Principal Jack McFarland and Assistant Principal Tammy Hall talked to eighth grade parents about the Structure and Strategies of the program.
Students entering the ninth grade will choose one of four thematic class clusters called Gateways. Those Gateways are Patriot Strong and Patriot Journey (a semester of career exploration in engineering and sports medicine) and Patriot Expression and Patriot Valor (a semester of career exploration in business and Microsoft).
Ninth grade Gateways lead to 10th grade Pathways. Together, Gateways and Pathways are the foundation of four years of learning and preparing students for post high school goals.

post_text:
Did you know January is National Soup Month? Help us help our community by participating in Thoreau High's First Annual Souper Bowl! For each canned item a class donate's their grade will receive 1 point. For example if a student brought in 5 canned items, their class will receive 5 points. The highest scoring grade/team will be our 2020 Thoreau High Souper Bowl Champions!

As a community based/service learning project, our school will be collecting and donating the canned food items to our local food pantry, "Native Hope Food Pantry-St. Bonaventure Indian School". Help us collect canned food items such as soups, canned vegetables, fruit, beans, canned meat, etc.) Turn in canned items beginning January 14th to Mrs. Swan's classroom (Room 108). Will your favorite class/team be our next 2020 Souper Bowl Champions?

post_text: Navajo Technical University is presenting 2020 Youth Ranch Camp June 21-26, 2020 & Safeguarding Natural Heritage: Summer Youth Camp May 31-June 12, 2020. This is a totally FREE opportunity that will give students to explore career pathways in Health Science, Business, just to name a few. Students will have the opportunity to have college experience by staying on NTU's Campus in their dorms. You are encourage to identify any students that may be interested in these opportunities and refer them. All contact information are on the flyers. The program is competitive.

post_text:
The STEM Challenge Team was victorious! They worked very hard and had to present to 4 judges and the other attendees of the Showcase. The representative from Intel was impressed by their project enough to award them the championship. The students received varsity letters for their participation along with a $500 award. They will also be among the first champions in the Inaugural NM Governor’s STEM Challenge.
Thank you for all your support during the past few months.
Please congratulate the winning team members when you see them: Bryan Chee, Matthew Manuelito, Tahira Mason, and Cypress Mike.-Drew Hileman
Congratulations to our Tohatchi High School Students!
